          "$type": "text",
          "text": "{\"week_number\":1,\"phase_type\":\"Base\",\"weekly_target_km\":10,\"is_deload_week\":false,\"days\":[{\"day_of_week\":0,\"slot_type\":\"Rest\",\"workout_type\":null,\"notes\":\"Full rest day. Let your body absorb the work from last week. Gentle foot mobility or calf stretching is fine if it feels good.\"},{\"day_of_week\":1,\"slot_type\":\"Run\",\"workout_type\":\"Easy\",\"notes\":\"20-min easy run at 5:58/km. Walk breaks welcome at any sign of foot discomfort — no need to push through stiffness. This is your foundation run for the week.\"},{\"day_of_week\":2,\"slot_type\":\"Rest\",\"workout_type\":null,\"notes\":\"Rest or very light walking. Keep the foot happy. Notice how it feels after yesterday's run — that feedback matters.\"},{\"day_of_week\":3,\"slot_type\":\"CrossTrain\",\"workout_type\":\"CrossTrain\",\"notes\":\"Optional low-impact cross-training: swimming, upper-body strength, or gentle cycling if your foot tolerates it. Keep it easy and enjoyable — this is active recovery, not a workout to conquer.\"},{\"day_of_week\":4,\"slot_type\":\"Rest\",\"workout_type\":null,\"notes\":\"Rest day. Two runs this week is plenty at this stage. Trust the process.\"},{\"day_of_week\":5,\"slot_type\":\"Rest\",\"workout_type\":null,\"notes\":\"Rest and prepare for your Saturday long run. Light foot mobility work or calf raises (if cleared) can be a good pre-run ritual.\"},{\"day_of_week\":6,\"slot_type\":\"Run\",\"workout_type\":\"LongRun\",\"notes\":\"20-min easy long run at 5:58/km — your longest effort of the week. Walk breaks built in from the start every 8–10 min if helpful, or at any foot discomfort. Soft surface preferred if available. This is your anchor workout.\"}],\"week_summary\":\"Welcome back to structured training, James. This first week mirrors what you've been doing successfully — two easy runs capped at 20 minutes each, both at your easy pace of 5:58/km. Your recent training history shows your foot is responding well, and that's genuinely encouraging progress. The goal this week isn't to push further — it's to confirm that your body handles consistent, gentle load without complaint. Think of this as laying the first brick. The optional cross-training on Wednesday is there if you want it, but rest is equally valid. How your foot feels after each run is your most important data point right now.\"}"
        }
      ]
